during the late eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries. Drawing on a wide range of evidence, this volume is a carefully researched investigation into the ethnohistory of the Pacific Northwest during the period of European exploration of the region. The book supplements the archeological evidence from the area with a detailed investigation of the journals, diaries, and sketchbooks of Russian, Spanish, and English explorers and traders who reached the region, as well as artifacts that those explorers and traders obtained on their expeditions and that are now held in museums worldwide. In doing so, Gunther's research extends anthropological study of the region a century earlier, and sheds light on the understudied tribal cultures of the Haida and the Tlingit. The volume contains splendid reproductions of contemporary drawings, and appendices mapping the museum locations of artifacts and describing the processes of native technology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aindigenous populations, native peoples, north america, american cultures, northwest coast, 18th century, history, historical inquiry, historians, fur traders, early explorers, ethnography, ethnographic research, exploration, ethnohistorical method, artifacts, gathering, collection, anthropology, anthropological studies, anthropologists, ethnobotanist, ethnobotany, salish, makah.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1960-1989z978311066784440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226310879423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226310879/original  a978-3-11-066784-4  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1960-1989c1960d1989  aGBV-deGruyter-alles